The result is a collection that offers a capsule retrospective
of Morandi=E2=80=99s entire body of work. A printmaker, painter, and waterc=
olorist, Morandi had three main subjects of his work: endless variations on=
 tabletop still lifes, floral images, and landscapes. In the Magnani collec=
tion, you=E2=80=99ll see the delicate interplay between form and image.=C2=
=A0

=C2=A0

Its presence in New York is the product of at least two years of effort by =
Leiber, who has an affinity for Italian art,
and noticed several years ago that the Magnani-Rocca foundation closed in t=
he winter. So Leiber began the process of bringing Magnani=E2=80=99s Morand=
is to New York=E2=80=94no small feat, given that Morandi=E2=80=99s quiet, o=
ften gnostic work is jealously guarded by the Italian state, especially now=
 that the defense of its cultural heritage has become a right-wing talking =
point for Giorgia Meloni=E2=80=99s nationalist government. Leiber was sweat=
ing export permits until the very last minute.

But in the end, he got them, and New York got its second spectacular Morand=
i show in the short span of four months. As Wall Power readers know from ou=
r interview ( https://puck.news/art-dealer-mattia-de-luca-on-his-new-giorgi=
o-morandi-pop-up/?utm_campaign=3DWall+Power+-+SUBSCRIBERS+%281%2F28%2F25%29=
&utm_content=3DWall+Power+-+SUBSCRIBERS+%281%2F28%2F25%29&utm_medium=3Demai=
l_action&utm_source=3Dcustomer.io&utm_term=3Df6c60617da42abd12a ) with Matt=
ia De Luca about his pop-up of Morandi=E2=80=99s work last fall, the first =
show offered a very different take on the same subject. De Luca was captiva=
ted by
the subtle differences and similarities, often decades apart, in the way Mo=
randi treated his still lifes, landscapes, and floral paintings. De Luca ga=
thered as much of Morandi=E2=80=99s work together as he could, to allow vie=
wers to see the carefully calibrated use of light and color, and the artist=
=E2=80=99s exploration of the way forms could be presented to elicit emotio=
ns.

Giorgio Morandi, Autoritratto (Self-Portrait), 1925

In the Magnani collection, Morandi fans will see the artist=E2=80=99s extra=
ordinary
technical skill. At one extreme is the incredible depth that Morandi achiev=
ed by varying the cross-hatching in his etchings. At the other is the minim=
alist abstraction of his watercolor still lifes and landscapes. In between,=
 we see a landscape painting with half the canvas dominated by a blank wall=
, prefiguring pop art images that would come later in the 1960s, and anothe=
r image of bottles standing like sentries in a metaphysical landscape, not =
to mention an actual metaphysical work from the
artist=E2=80=99s youth, and an enigmatic self-portrait. All of these works =
are presented in Morandi=E2=80=99s idiosyncratic palette of muted, unsatura=
ted colors.

=E2=80=9CA Park Avenue-Type of Painting=E2=80=9D
------------------------------------

None of the works in the Zwirner show are for sale, obviously. But
having two remarkable Morandi shows in New York in quick succession cannot =
but help generate more interest in, and demand for, the artist. There are o=
nly about 1,300 paintings. The etchings, for reasons I don=E2=80=99t really=
 understand, trade at prices in the low five figures, sometimes falling bel=
ow $10,000.=C2=A0

=C2=A0

Sales of Morandi=E2=80=99s work began to pick up around 2007, the first yea=
r his auction volume topped $10
million. Overall auction totals would wax and wane until 2018, when the vol=
ume topped $20 million. The next year, volume stayed just above that mark, =
but the trend was unsustainable and auction sales fell below $10 million ag=
ain, rising from just above $7 million in 2020 and 2021, to $11.8 million i=
n 2023. Last year, Morandi=E2=80=99s auction volume dropped again, to just =
over $5 million.=C2=A0

=C2=A0

But the falling auction volume is
less an indicator of evaporating interest than it is an issue of supply, an=
d whether to sell at auction at all. That said, the average price of a Mora=
ndi over the past decade has steadily risen, even accounting for the usual =
oscillations in the market. Put another way, the highs are getting higher, =
and the lows are also getting higher.=C2=A0

