In 2007, a 1920 Morandi still life set an auction record for the
artist of $2.7 million. In 2015, a 1939 still life was sold at auction for =
$3.9 million. Then, in 2018, David Rockefeller=E2=80=99s oval 1940 still li=
fe made an auction price of $4.3 million, defining the upper end of the Mor=
andi market. Since then, a 1954 still life sold for $3.8 million in Novembe=
r 2021, and a 1959 still life made $3.5 million a year later. Meanwhile, an=
other four works auctioned above the $2 million mark, even as the frequency=
 of sales slowed, possibly reflecting the
combined efforts of De Luca and Leiber to match buyers and sellers on the p=
rivate market.=C2=A0

=C2=A0

When I asked De Luca about Morandi=E2=80=99s pricing, he cautioned that he =
was not a trophy artist. Important collectors like Rockefeller might own th=
e works, but Morandi=E2=80=99s paintings and etchings are more quiet and co=
ntemplative than show-offy. Leiber added that the Italian government=E2=80=
=99s reluctance to see Morandis leave
Italy adds uncertainty for potential bidders and mutes the auction market.=
=C2=A0

=C2=A0

Those are good explanations, but I decided to check in with a European coll=
ector who happens to be a real Morandi aficionado. He offered four reasons =
that Morandis don=E2=80=99t sell for big prices. First, =E2=80=9Cthey=E2=80=
=99re intimate paintings,=E2=80=9D he said, =E2=80=9Cnot in-your-face, cont=
rary to Fontana. It=E2=80=99s a bit like a smallish
Ryman=E2=80=94you might pay $18 million for a large Ryman, or a large Fonta=
na, but not for a small one.=E2=80=9D=C2=A0

=C2=A0

Then there was the palette issue. The colors, he said, were =E2=80=9Ctoo su=
btle to please the current market.=E2=80=9D And the muted tones read old mo=
ney and conservative, =E2=80=9Ca Park Avenue-type of painting.=E2=80=9D Als=
o, although the Chinese began acquiring Morandi=E2=80=99s works more than a=
 decade ago after the painter
Zeng Fanzhi started buying and his collectors followed, it=E2=80=99s still =
a very Italian market. (Though this collector said that the export-license =
issue wasn=E2=80=99t that big a deal since most of the prewar works=E2=80=
=94the ones the government keeps a watchful eye on=E2=80=94are already in m=
useums.)=C2=A0

=C2=A0

My informant=E2=80=99s final comment was startling, and encapsulated Morand=
i=E2=80=99s simultaneous blessing and curse.
=E2=80=9CMorandi is a connoisseur=E2=80=99s artist,=E2=80=9D he wrote, =E2=
=80=9Cand connoisseurs don=E2=80=99t make a market these days.=E2=80=9D

