1f4c0ee16b9cf4681abf550bb531784d7dcde02548c0aaaf0b4ad528e1" style=3D"text-d=
ecoration:underline;color:#d40000;">interview</a> with <strong>Mattia De Lu=
ca</strong> about his pop-up of Morandi=E2=80=99s work last fall, the first=
 show offered a very different take on the same subject. De Luca was captiv=
ated by
the subtle differences and similarities, often decades apart, in the way Mo=
randi treated his still lifes, landscapes, and floral paintings. De Luca ga=
thered as much of Morandi=E2=80=99s work together as he could, to allow vie=
wers to see the carefully calibrated use of light and color, and the artist=
