;Inter&#39;,&#39;Arial&#39;;font-size:17px;font-weight:400;letter-spacing:0=
px;line-height:150%;text-align:left;mso-line-height-alt:25.5px;"><p style=
=3D"margin:0;margin-bottom:0px;">In 2007, a 1920 Morandi still life set an =
auction record for the
artist of $2.7 million. In 2015, a 1939 still life was sold at auction for =
$3.9 million. Then, in 2018, <strong>David Rockefeller</strong>=E2=80=99s o=
val 1940 still life made an auction price of $4.3 million, defining the upp=
er end of the Morandi market. Since then, a 1954 still life sold for $3.8 m=
illion in November 2021, and a 1959 still life made $3.5 million a year lat=
er. Meanwhile, another four works auctioned above the $2 million mark, even=
 as the frequency of sales slowed, possibly reflecting the
combined efforts of De Luca and Leiber to match buyers and sellers on the p=
rivate market.=C2=A0</p><p style=3D"margin:0;margin-bottom:0px;">=C2=A0</p>=
<p style=3D"margin:0;margin-bottom:0px;">When I asked De Luca about Morandi=
=E2=80=99s pricing, he cautioned that he was not a trophy artist. Important=
 collectors like Rockefeller might own the works, but Morandi=E2=80=99s pai=
ntings and etchings are more quiet and contemplative than show-offy. Leiber=
 added that the Italian government=E2=80=99s reluctance to see Morandis lea=
ve
Italy adds uncertainty for potential bidders and mutes the auction market.=
=C2=A0</p><p style=3D"margin:0;margin-bottom:0px;">=C2=A0</p><p style=3D"ma=
rgin:0;margin-bottom:0px;">Those are good explanations, but I decided to ch=
eck in with a European collector who happens to be a real Morandi aficionad=
o. He offered four reasons that Morandis don=E2=80=99t sell for big prices.=
 First, =E2=80=9Cthey=E2=80=99re intimate paintings,=E2=80=9D he said, =E2=
=80=9Cnot in-your-face, contrary to <strong>Fontana</strong>. It=E2=80=99s =
a bit like a smallish
<strong>Ryman</strong>=E2=80=94you might pay $18 million for a large Ryman,=
 or a large Fontana, but not for a small one.=E2=80=9D=C2=A0</p><p style=3D=
"margin:0;margin-bottom:0px;">=C2=A0</p><p style=3D"margin:0;margin-bottom:=
0px;">Then there was the palette issue. The colors, he said, were =E2=80=9C=
too subtle to please the current market.=E2=80=9D And the muted tones read =
old money and conservative, =E2=80=9Ca Park Avenue-type of painting.=E2=80=
=9D Also, although the Chinese began acquiring Morandi=E2=80=99s works more=
 than a decade ago after the painter
<strong>Zeng</strong> <strong>Fanzhi</strong> started buying and his collec=
tors followed, it=E2=80=99s still a very Italian market. (Though this colle=
ctor said that the export-license issue wasn=E2=80=99t <em>that</em> big a =
deal since most of the prewar works=E2=80=94the ones the government keeps a=
 watchful eye on=E2=80=94are already in museums.)=C2=A0</p><p style=3D"marg=
in:0;margin-bottom:0px;">=C2=A0</p><p style=3D"margin:0;">My informant=E2=
=80=99s final comment was startling, and encapsulated Morandi=E2=80=99s sim=
ultaneous blessing and curse.
=E2=80=9CMorandi is a connoisseur=E2=80=99s artist,=E2=80=9D he wrote, =E2=
=80=9Cand connoisseurs don=E2=80=99t make a market these days.=E2=80=9D</p>=
</div>
